<paragraph blockId="0.[151,1436,1594,1998]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">
This genus can be distinguished from the other genera of the 
<taxonomicName box="[854,1020,1594,1617]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Megalurothrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[854,1020,1594,1617]" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">Megalurothrips</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus-group by the following set of characters (
<bibRefCitation author="Mirab-balou" box="[273,565,1629,1652]" pageId="0" pageNumber="488" refString="Mirab-balou, M. &amp; Chen, X. X. (2011) The Megalurothrips genus-group in Iran (Thysanoptera: Thripidae). Munis Entomology &amp; Zoology, 6 (2), 944 - 952. Available from: http: // www. munisentzool. org / yayin / vol 6 / issue 2 / 944 - 952. pdf (accessed 5 November 2015)" type="journal article" year="2011">
Mirab-balou &amp; Chen 
<number box="[508,565,1629,1652]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="2011.0">2011</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). Tarsi 
<number box="[644,657,1629,1652]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="2.0">2</number>
-segmented; fore tibiae and fore tarsus with or without tubercles or claw like processes at apex (
<bibRefCitation author="Xie" box="[400,566,1663,1686]" pageId="0" pageNumber="488" refString="Xie, Y. H., Zhang, H. R. &amp; Mound, L. A. (2010) A new species from southwestern China of the holarctic genus Odontothrips (Thysanoptera: Thripidae). Zootaxa, 2729, 53 - 57." type="journal article" year="2010">
Xie et al. 
<number box="[508,566,1663,1686]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="2010.0">2010</number>
</bibRefCitation>
); the base of antennal segment VI greatly elongated; head with 
<number box="[1253,1266,1663,1686]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="3.0">3</number>
pairs of ocellar setae, pair III longer than other head setae; postocular arranged in one row; pronotum with 
<number box="[1167,1180,1698,1721]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="2.0">2</number>
pairs of similarly long posteroangular setae; ferna entire; mesothoracic sternopleural sutures present; metanotal median pair of setae situated at the anterior margin; spinula present on mesosternum but absent on metasternum (
<figureCitation box="[1021,1087,1767,1790]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 5" captionStartId="1.[151,258,1968,1990]" captionTargetBox="[201,1370,214,1893]" captionTargetId="figure@1.[173,1388,194,1911]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 5. Odontothrips moringa. (1) female; (2) Male and female in copulation; (2) female; (3) Head and pronotum, female; (4) Meso- &amp; metasterna, female; (5) fore wing, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/254886/files/figure.png" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">
Fig. 
<number box="[1071,1087,1767,1790]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="4.0">
<docIssue box="[1071,1087,1767,1790]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484">4</docIssue>
</number>
</figureCitation>
); setae on first vein of fore wing interrupted subapically, with 
<number box="[463,502,1802,1825]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
distal setae, second vein with complete row of setae; tergite VIII with posteromarginal comb but absent in middle; abdominal tergites and laterotergites without accessory setae; sternite VII with S 
<number box="[1361,1372,1837,1860]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="1.0">1</number>
setae ahead of posterior margin; tergite X of female with incomplete longitudinal split; male abdominal sternites without pore areas, tergite IX of male with or without pair of processes and if present, these are either short, stout, thorn-like or sometimes sigmoid shaped; endotheca of phallus with or without endothecal spines supported by canaliculi (
<bibRefCitation author="Pitkin" pageId="0" pageNumber="488" refString="Pitkin, B. R. (1972) A revision of the flower-living genus Odontothrips Amyot &amp; Serville (Thysanoptera: Thripidae). Bulletin of the British Museum of Natural History (Entomology), 26, 371 - 402." type="journal article" year="1972">
Pitkin 
<number box="[151,209,1975,1998]" pageId="0" pageNumber="484" value="1972.0">1972</number>
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
